Java Collections provide ready-made data structures for every need.

```java
// List: ordered, allows duplicates
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>(); // O(1) get, O(n) insert mid
List<String> linked = new LinkedList<>(); // O(1) insert ends, O(n) get

// Set: unique elements
Set<Integer> hashSet = new HashSet<>();   // O(1) ops, no order
Set<Integer> treeSet = new TreeSet<>();   // O(log n), sorted

// Map: key-value pairs
Map<String,Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("a", 1);
map.getOrDefault("b", 0); // safe get
map.computeIfAbsent("c", k -> k.length());

// Queue / Deque
Deque<String> deque = new ArrayDeque<>();
deque.offerFirst("front"); deque.offerLast("back");

// Frequency count pattern
Map<Character,Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
for (char c : "hello".toCharArray())
  freq.merge(c, 1, Integer::sum);
```

Generics enable type-safe reusable code without casting.

```java
// Generic class
class Pair<A, B> {
  final A first; final B second;
  Pair(A a, B b) { first = a; second = b; }
}

// Bounded type parameter
<T extends Comparable<T>> T max(T a, T b) {
  return a.compareTo(b) >= 0 ? a : b;
}

// Wildcards (PECS: Producer Extends, Consumer Super)
void readAll(List<? extends Number> list) {
  for (Number n : list) System.out.println(n); // read only
}
void addNumbers(List<? super Integer> list) {
  list.add(42); // write only
}

// Type erasure: generics exist only at compile time
// List<String> and List<Integer> are both List at runtime
// Cannot do: new T(), instanceof List<String>, T[]

class Box<T> {
  T value;
  Box(T v) { value = v; }
  <R> Box<R> map(Function<T,R> f) { return new Box<>(f.apply(value)); }
}
```

Java exceptions form a hierarchy rooted at Throwable.

```java
// Checked: must declare or catch (IOException, SQLException)
// Unchecked: RuntimeException and subclasses (NPE, IAE, ISE)
// Error: JVM-level, do not catch (OutOfMemoryError, StackOverflow)

// Custom exception
class InsufficientFundsException extends Exception {
  private final double amount;
  InsufficientFundsException(double a) {
    super("Insufficient funds: need " + a);
    this.amount = a;
  }
  double getAmount() { return amount; }
}

// try-with-resources (auto-closes Closeable)
try (var conn = getConnection();
     var ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {
  ps.executeUpdate();
} catch (SQLException e) {
  throw new DataAccessException("DB error", e); // preserve cause
}

// Multi-catch
try { riskyOp(); }
catch (IOException | ParseException e) { handle(e); }
finally { cleanup(); } // always runs
```
Never swallow exceptions silently. Always wrap with context when re-throwing.

Streams enable declarative data processing pipelines.

```java
List<Employee> emps = getEmployees();

// Pipeline: source -> intermediate ops -> terminal op
double avgSalary = emps.stream()
  .filter(e -> e.getDept().equals("Eng"))
  .mapToDouble(Employee::getSalary)
  .average()
  .orElse(0.0);

// Collectors
Map<String, List<Employee>> byDept =
  emps.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Employee::getDept));

Map<String, Double> avgByDept =
  emps.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(
      Employee::getDept,
      Collectors.averagingDouble(Employee::getSalary)));

// FlatMap
List<String> words = sentences.stream()
  .flatMap(s -> Arrays.stream(s.split(" ")))
  .distinct().sorted().collect(Collectors.toList());

// Functional interfaces
Function<String,Integer> len = String::length;
Predicate<String> notEmpty = s -> !s.isEmpty();
BiFunction<Integer,Integer,Integer> add = Integer::sum;
```

Java concurrency enables parallel execution but requires careful coordination.

```java
// Prefer ExecutorService over raw Thread
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);
Future<Integer> future = pool.submit(() -> compute());
int result = future.get(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
pool.shutdown();

// synchronized — mutual exclusion
class SafeCounter {
  private int count = 0;
  synchronized void increment() { count++; }
  synchronized int get() { return count; }
}

// AtomicInteger — lock-free for simple ops
AtomicInteger counter = new AtomicInteger(0);
counter.incrementAndGet();
counter.compareAndSet(expected, newVal); // CAS

// CompletableFuture — async composition
CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> fetchUser(id))
  .thenApply(user -> enrich(user))
  .thenAccept(u -> save(u))
  .exceptionally(ex -> { log(ex); return null; });

// volatile — visibility guarantee (no atomicity)
volatile boolean running = true;
```
Deadlock: threads hold locks and wait for each other. Prevention: always acquire locks in the same order.

Understanding the JVM enables writing performant Java and diagnosing production issues.

```
JVM Memory Layout:
┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Heap: objects, class instances     │
│  ├─ Young Gen (Eden + S0 + S1)      │
│  └─ Old Gen (Tenured)               │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Stack (per thread): frames,        │
│    local vars, operand stack        │
├─────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Metaspace: class metadata (JDK 8+) │
│  Code Cache: JIT-compiled code      │
└─────────────────────────────────────┘

// GC Roots: local vars, static refs, JNI refs
// Reachable from roots = alive; else eligible for GC

